Montevideo BFD/non-focalized graphs:

Graph 1: Montevideo BFD nuclear configurations (i.e., pitch accent + boundary tone) (not by gender or age).

Graph 1: A poisson regression was run where the dependent variable was n (number of occurrences) and the independent variable was tone (only the tones L*L% and L+H*L& were included). The model revealed a significant difference between these two levels (β = -1.08; p < .05).

Graph 2: Montevideo BFD nuclear configurations (i.e., pitch accent + boundary tone) (not by gender or age).

Graph 2: A poisson regression was run where the dependent variable was n (number of occurrences) and the independent variable was tone (6 levels for this model: H*, H+L*, L+¡H*, L+<H*, L+H* and deaccented(DA)). The intercept of the model is DA, so the differences which are significant (L+<H* and L+¡H*) only tell us that these two pitch accents are predicted by the model to be produced significantly more than deaccented tokens. The do not tell us about all possible comparisons, and we would need to do post-hoc tests for this. It would be best to do post-hoc tests only as needed, or re-level to models to change the reference if you want a particular tone to be the baseline that the other tones are compared to.

Durazno BFD/non-focalized graphs:

Graph 14: Durazno BFD nuclear configurations (i.e., pitch accent + boundary tone) (not by gender or age).

Graph 14: A poisson regression was run where the dependent variable was n (number of occurrences) and the independent variable was tone (the tones L*L% and L+H*L% and N/A were included). The model revealed a significant difference between L*L% and L+H*L% two levels (β = -1.06; p < .05). and between L*L% and N/A -0.37.

Graph 15: Durazno BFD nuclear configurations (i.e., pitch accent + boundary tone) (not by gender or age).

Graph 15: A poisson regression was run where the dependent variable was n (number of occurrences) and the independent variable was tone (3 levels for this model: L*+H, L+<H* and L+H*). The intercept of the model is L*+H, so, like the model for Montevideo, all differences which are significant only tell us that these two pitch accents are predicted by the model to be produced significantly more than L*+H tokens.
